div.p:
“ (So flowed, so sanded, and their heads are hung With ears that sweep away the
                    morning dew. Crook-knee’d, and dewlapt, like Thessalian bulls; Slow in pursuit;
                    but match’d in mouth like bells, Each under each :)”

Nobleman. Huntsman, I charge thee, tender well my hounds;
                    Brach Merriman,—the poor cur is emboss’d, And couple Clowder with the
                    deep-raouth’d brach.

I would not lose the dog for twenty pound.Huntsman. Why, Belman is as good as he, my lord; He cried
                    upon it at the meerest loss, And twice to-day pick’d out the dullest scent;
                    Trust me, I take him for the better dog.
